{"id":"gr-qc/0002025","submitter":"Enrico Montanari","authors":"Enrico Montanari, Mirco Calura (University of Ferrara and INFN sezione\n  di Ferrara, Italy)","title":"Exact plane gravitational waves and electromagnetic fields","comments":"14 pages; revtex; accepted for publication in Annals of Physics","journal-ref":"Annals Phys. 282 (2000) 449-470","doi":"10.1006/aphy.2000.6045","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The behaviour of a \"test\" electromagnetic field in the background of an exact\ngravitational plane wave is investigated in the framework of Einstein's general\nrelativity. We have expressed the general solution to the de Rham equations as\na Fourier-like integral. In the general case we have reduced the problem to a\nset of ordinary differential equations and have explicitly written the solution\nin the case of linear polarization of the gravitational wave. We have expressed\nour results by means of Fermi Normal Coordinates (FNC), which define the proper\nreference frame of the laboratory. Moreover we have provided some \"gedanken\nexperiments\", showing that an external gravitational wave induces measurable\neffects of non tidal nature via electromagnetic interaction. Consequently it is\nnot possible to eliminate gravitational effects on electromagnetic field, even\nin an arbitrarily small spatial region around an observer freely falling in the\nfield of a gravitational wave. This is opposite to the case of mechanical\ninteraction involving measurements of geodesic deviation effects. This\nbehaviour is not in contrast with the principle of equivalence, which applies\nto arbitrarily small region of both space and time.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 6 Feb 2000 17:49:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
